@bougakovgeorge reproduction steps using a browser:
1. install [User-Agent Switcher - chrome extension](https://chrome.google.com/webstore/detail/user-agent-switcher/clddifkhlkcojbojppdojfeeikdkgiae?hl=en)
2. create a new user-agent
3. name your new user-agent whatever you want  {F314226}
4. set user-agent value to: `<script>alert(0)</script>`  {F314226}
5. select the new user agent 
6. start one of the test examples: `node test/express.js`
7. browse: `http://localhost:3000` using chrome
8. the XSS value will be reflected but not triggered due the fact its reflected inside JSON context.

From here we know that the user agent is not sanitized, let's edit one of the examples (express.js) simulating a scenario of developer who want to display the user agent of the visitor:

1. edit test/express.js:

```javascript
...
app.get('/', function (req, res) {
    res.send("User-Agent: " + req.useragent.source);
});
...
```
2. save changes and run again the server: `node express.js`
3. visit `http://localhost:3000` using chrome (make sure user-agent switch is on and using custom payload)
4. XSS window should pop up. {F314225}

